  "prompt": "Why is Bogota cold?",
  "response": "Bogot\u00e1, the capital city of Colombia, is located in the Andes Mountains at an altitude of approximately 2,640 meters (8,660 feet) above sea level. This high elevation is the primary reason why Bogot\u00e1 has a relatively cold climate compared to other cities in Colombia, which are generally warmer due to their lower altitudes.\n\nHere are some key factors contributing to Bogot\u00e1's cool climate:\n\n1. **Altitude**: Higher altitudes generally have cooler temperatures because the air is thinner and less capable of retaining heat. For every 1,000 meters (3,280 feet) increase in elevation, the temperature typically drops by about 6.5\u00b0C (11.7\u00b0F).\n\n2. **Andean Climate**: Bogot\u00e1 is situated in the Andes Mountains, which have a unique climate characterized by cool temperatures and significant variations in weather throughout the day. The city experiences a subtropical highland climate, also known as a \"Cfb\" climate in the K\u00f6ppen classification, which is mild and rainy.\n\n3. **Proximity to the Equator**: Although Bogot\u00e1 is close to the equator, which generally results in warm temperatures, the high altitude counteracts this effect, leading to cooler conditions.\n\n4. **Weather Patterns**: Bogot\u00e1 experiences frequent rain showers and overcast conditions, which can also contribute to the perception of a colder climate. The city has a relatively consistent temperature range throughout the year, with average highs around 14-20\u00b0C (57-68\u00b0F) and average lows around 6-10\u00b0C (43-50\u00b0F).\n\nOverall, the combination of high altitude, mountainous terrain, and specific weather patterns results in Bogot\u00e1's cooler climate compared to other parts of Colombia.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
